abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
snippet: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
lead_paragraph: This just in: analysts for big securities firms are bullish about the stocks they cover. Many do not spend enough time on fundamental research. Some face pressure from their investment banking colleagues to maintain positive ratings on companies. lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
snippet: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
lead_paragraph: This just in: analysts for big securities firms are bullish about the stocks they cover. Many do not spend enough time on fundamental research. Some face pressure from their investment banking colleagues to maintain positive ratings on companies. Sometimes the pressure comes from the companies themselves, or even from big shareholders, who would rather not hear bad news.

abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.
snippet: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.
lead_paragraph: ONE of the upsides in the Enron ( news/quote ) collapse is that investors have been awakened from their perilous dream state, brought on by the beautiful stock market bubble of the late 1990's. Now all of these players are viewed, justifiably, with more of a gimlet eye.

abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.

lead_paragraph: This just in: analysts for big securities firms are bullish about the stocks they cover. Many do not spend enough time on fundamental research. abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. abstract: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.
snippet: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.
lead_paragraph: ONE of the upsides in the Enron ( news/quote ) collapse is that investors have been awakened from their perilous dream state, brought on by the beautiful stock market bubble of the late 1990's. Before Enron, investors believed every utterance from corporate executives, Wall Street analysts and prestigious accounting firms. Now all of these players are viewed, justifiably, with more of a gimlet eye.

abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
snippet: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
lead_paragraph: This just in: analysts for big securities firms are bullish about the stocks they cover. Many do not spend enough time on fundamental research. Some face pressure from their investment banking colleagues to maintain positive ratings on companies. Sometimes the pressure comes from the companies themselves, or even from big shareholders, who would rather not hear bad news.

abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.

lead_paragraph: ONE of the upsides in the Enron ( news/quote ) collapse is that investors have been awakened from their perilous dream state, brought on by the beautiful stock market bubble of the late 1990's. Now all of these players are viewed, justifiably, with more of a gimlet eye.

abstract: Scarred but largely unbowed, many investors say the stock market is still the place to be, even as they acknowledge that the record bull run of the 1990's was probably a once-in-a-lifetime phenomenon.
snippet: Scarred but largely unbowed, many investors say the stock market is still the place to be, even as they acknowledge that the record bull run of the 1990's was probably a once-in-a-lifetime phenomenon.

abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.

abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.

lead_paragraph: ONE of the upsides in the Enron ( news/quote ) collapse is that investors have been awakened from their perilous dream state, brought on by the beautiful stock market bubble of the late 1990's. Now all of these players are viewed, justifiably, with more of a gimlet eye.

abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
snippet: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
lead_paragraph: This just in: analysts for big securities firms are bullish about the stocks they cover. Many do not spend enough time on fundamental research. Some face pressure from their investment banking colleagues to maintain positive ratings on companies. Sometimes the pressure comes from the companies themselves, or even from big shareholders, who would rather not hear bad news.

abstract: Lawmakers investigating Enron's collapse criticized financial analysts for continuing to urge investors to buy stock even as the company headed toward bankruptcy.
snippet: Lawmakers investigating Enron's collapse criticized financial analysts for continuing to urge investors to buy stock even as the company headed toward bankruptcy.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Feb. 27 — Lawmakers investigating the collapse of Enron ( news/quote ) turned their attention to Wall Street today, criticizing financial analysts for continuing to urge investors to buy Enron stock even as the company headed toward bankruptcy. abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

abstract: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: Kenneth L. Lay, Enron's former chief, invoked his right not to testify before a Senate committee today, but not before enduring more than an hour of denunciation by lawmakers.
snippet: Kenneth L. Lay, Enron's former chief, invoked his right not to testify before a Senate committee today, but not before enduring more than an hour of denunciation by lawmakers.

abstract: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
snippet: In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that Enron misled its employees and investors.
lead_paragraph: BELLE, W.Va., Jan. 22 — In a sharp change of tone, President Bush said today he was "outraged" that the Enron Corporation , which heavily contributed to his campaigns over the last decade, misled its employees and investors, including his mother-in-law, who apparently lost more than $8,000 in an ill-timed investment in the energy company's stock. For the first time, Mr. Bush called for government action to force greater corporate disclosure of financial information.

snippet: Lobbyists for Enron are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two.
lead_paragraph: Lobbyists for Enron ( news/quote ) who once roamed aggressively through Washington are few and far between, now that its lobbying office has been cut from six people to two. But the lobbying industry has found momentum from Enron's collapse: accountants are beefing up their lobbying ranks on the Hill. The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has hired former aides to Newt Gingrich and Bob Kerrey, along with the veteran lobbyists and former congressmen Vin Weber, Republican from Minnesota, and Vic Fazio, a Democrat from California. Arthur Andersen, the accounting firm dismissed by Enron earlier this month, has supplemented its in-house lobbying staff of two dozen by hiring a top Washington firm, the Duberstein Group, run by a former Reagan White House chief of staff, Kenneth M. Duberstein, as well as former Senator John Danforth, a Missouri Republican.

abstract: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
snippet: In his first State of the Union address, President Bush sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Jan. 29 — President Bush tonight told Americans that "our war against terror is only beginning," and sent new warnings to terrorists around the world and to three nations — Iran, Iraq and North Korea. Using unusually strong language, he charged that the three "constitute an axis of evil," evoking a word once used to describe the alliance of Germany, Italy and Japan during World War II.

abstract: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.
snippet: That corporate executives act as spinmeisters was not exactly breaking news. That accounting firms would sign off on opaque financial statements, now that was breathtaking.
lead_paragraph: ONE of the upsides in the Enron ( news/quote ) collapse is that investors have been awakened from their perilous dream state, brought on by the beautiful stock market bubble of the late 1990's. Now all of these players are viewed, justifiably, with more of a gimlet eye.

snippet: Jeffrey K. Skilling said at a hearing that he did not lie to Congress earlier this month about his role in Enron's collapse.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Feb. 26 — Jeffrey K. abstract: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
snippet: Pretty much everyone agrees that Wall Street analysts are too bullish. And that bullishness does not serve investors well, lawmakers agreed Wednesday.
lead_paragraph: This just in: analysts for big securities firms are bullish about the stocks they cover. Many do not spend enough time on fundamental research. Some face pressure from their investment banking colleagues to maintain positive ratings on companies. Sometimes the pressure comes from the companies themselves, or even from big shareholders, who would rather not hear bad news.

abstract: Lawmakers investigating Enron's collapse criticized financial analysts for continuing to urge investors to buy stock even as the company headed toward bankruptcy.
snippet: Lawmakers investigating Enron's collapse criticized financial analysts for continuing to urge investors to buy stock even as the company headed toward bankruptcy.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON, Feb. 27 — Lawmakers investigating the collapse of Enron ( news/quote ) turned their attention to Wall Street today, criticizing financial analysts for continuing to urge investors to buy Enron stock even as the company headed toward bankruptcy. Several members of Congress suggested that Wall Street firms' hunger for investment banking business and other conflicts kept them from leveling with investors.
